[[Category:Heraldry]]

[[File:The practical book of period furniture, treating of furniture of the English, American colonial and post-colonial and principal French periods (1914) (14778886135).jpg|thumb|A William and Mary style cabinet with jappanning.]]
What later came to be known as the '''William and Mary style''' is a [[furniture]] design common from 1700 to 1725 in the [[Netherlands]], the [[Kingdom of England]], the [[Kingdom of Scotland]], and later, in England's [[Thirteen Colonies|American colonies]]. It was a transitional style between [[Mannerism|Mannerist furniture]] and [[Queen Anne style furniture|Queen Anne furniture]]. Sturdy, emphasizing both straight lines and curves, and featuring elaborate carving and [[woodturning]], the style was one of the first to imitate Asian design elements such as [[japanning]].

==About the design==
In 1688, [[James II of England]] was deposed by his daughter, [[Mary II of England|Mary]], and her husband, [[William III of England|William of Orange]], in what came to be known as the "[[Glorious Revolution]]". From birth in 1650, William had reigned over five provinces of the [[Dutch Republic]], and Mary had lived in the Netherlands with him after their marriage in 1677.  William and Mary brought to their kingdoms a taste for Dutch furniture styles, as well as a number of Dutch furniture-makers.{{sfn|Butler|Johnson|Skibinski|1985|page=25}} Although movement toward what would come to be called the William and Mary style had begun during the reign of [[Charles II of England]], primarily due to the influence of his [[Portugal|Portuguese]]-born queen, [[Catherine of Braganza]], the style became defined and widely accepted during the reigns of William (d. 1702) and Mary (d. 1694),{{sfn|Davidson|Stillinger|1985|pages=108-109}} initially jointly and then after Mary's death, of William alone.

The William and Mary style was influenced by recent [[French furniture]] traditions, which in turn were influenced by [[Italy|Italian]] [[Baroque]] furniture designs.{{sfn|Butler|Johnson|Skibinski|1985|page=25}} William and Mary style furniture emphasized unity, so that all elements contributed to an overall shape or look. It also featured [[Relief#High relief|high relief]] carving, strong curves,{{Efn|Known as "Flemish curves".{{sfn|Davidson|Stillinger|1985|page=109}}}} and elaborate [[woodturning]].{{sfn|Butler|Johnson|Skibinski|1985|page=25}} Despite these elements, the style was fairly squat,{{sfn|Dillinger|2016|page=71}} heavy-looking, and obviously sturdy.{{sfn|Gura|2016|page=16}} Straight lines are common.{{sfn|Gura|2016|page=16}} Paint, [[wood stain|stain]]s, or different kind of wood were used to create contrasting colors, which was another element of this style.{{sfn|Butler|Johnson|Skibinski|1985|page=25}} [[Japanning]], a technique of [[varnish]]ing which was very popular at the time, was also used on this furniture design.{{sfn|Gura|2016|page=16}} For chairs, [[Caning (furniture)|woven cane]] seats{{sfn|Butler|Johnson|Skibinski|1985|page=26}} and heavily-scrolled backs predominated.{{sfn|Davidson|Stillinger|1985|page=109}} Toward the end of the style, cane-woven seats and backs had given way to leather, and straight or slightly angled backs had given way to serpentine forms.{{sfn|Dillinger|2016|page=71}}

Other decorative arts such as architecture, ceramics, silver, and textiles could also feature elements of the William and Mary style. The design movement had an extremely positive impact on the craftsmanship and quality of British furniture.{{sfn|''Grove Dictionary of Art''|2000|page=364}}

The William and Mary style was a transitional style between Mannerist and Queen Anne furniture.{{sfn|Dillinger|2016|page=71}} The William and Mary style was very popular in Britain from 1700 to 1725,{{sfn|Butler|Johnson|Skibinski|1985|page=25}} and in America until about 1735.{{sfn|Davidson|Stillinger|1985|page=109}} It was largely supplanted in both nations by [[Queen Anne style furniture]].{{sfn|Davidson|Stillinger|1985|page=109}}

===English variations===
[[Daniel Marot]], a [[French people|French]] [[Huguenots|Huguenot]], was employed by King William and Queen Mary to design furniture for them, and became deeply influential on English, Scottish, and Welsh furniture during this period.{{sfn|Dillinger|2016|page=71}} Dutch furniture craftsman [[Gerrit Jensen]] was appointed royal Cabinet Maker to the king and queen, and a great many works of his design were sold to wealthy British citizens of the day.{{sfn|''Grove Dictionary of Art''|2000|page=364}}

In Britain, case furniture{{Efn|Case furniture is any kind of furniture that suggests a box. Typical case furniture includes [[chest of drawers|bureaus]], [[cabinetry]], [[Chest (furniture)|chests]], [[cupboard]]s, [[desk]]s, and [[sideboard]]s.{{sfn|Thiel|2015|page=139}}}} in the William and Mary style tended to feature simple flat surfaces but exquisitely carved trim.{{sfn|Butler|Johnson|Skibinski|1985|page=25}} Provincial furniture-makers in Britain moved away from the woven cane seat, and developed the [[leather]]-covered wooden seat as a [[Vernacular architecture|vernacular]] design.{{sfn|Davidson|Stillinger|1985|page=109}} Split [[Spindle (furniture)|spindles]] also came into use, first rurally and then urbanly.{{sfn|Davidson|Stillinger|1985|page=109}}

The [[daybed]] was developed in Britain as part of the William and Mary style.{{sfn|Davidson|Stillinger|1985|page=109}} So, too, was the [[writing desk]], which was an adaptation of the bureau-cabinet.{{sfn|Butler|Johnson|Skibinski|1985|page=27}}{{Efn|The bureau-cabinet consisted of a chest of drawers atop which was a smaller set of shelves, pigeon-holes, and drawers set back from the front. A panel covered these drawers at an angle; when pulled forward and down, the panel served as a writing space. Atop the second set of drawers was a much taller third set of drawers, usually concealed behind two doors.{{sfn|Campbell|2006|pages=160-162}}}}

===American variations===
[[File:Side Chair, America, c. 1700, walnut and cane - Brooklyn Museum - DSC09086.JPG|thumb|A William and Mary style chair made in America.]]
American craftsmen working in the William and Mary style favored a tapered [[Foot (furniture)|scroll foot]] for their designs.{{sfn|Butler|Johnson|Skibinski|1985|page=25}} [[Juglans|Walnut]] and, to a lesser extent, [[maple]] were the preferred woods, with walnut [[burl]] [[Wood veneer|veneers]] and "ebonization" (black japanning) common.{{sfn|Butler|Johnson|Skibinski|1985|page=26}}

Over time, American forms of William and Mary furniture became simplified. Although the Baroque influence was still seen in the crests, feet, and scrolls, other elements and the overall look of pieces began to shed this influence in favor of plain but strong curves. American chairmakers began using woven cane in the [[Splat (furniture)|splats]] of chairs as well. For armchairs, American designers favored seats and splats covered in leather, attached with brass nails.{{sfn|Butler|Johnson|Skibinski|1985|page=26}}  In parts of America like [[New York (state)|New York]] and [[New Jersey]], which had a heavy Dutch cultural influence, the ''[[kast (furniture)|kast]]'' became popular. The ''kast'' was of Dutch origin, and featured a large drawer in the base unit. Atop the base were shelves concealed behind one or two heavy doors. An elaborate [[cornice]] usually ran along the upper edges. Influenced by the William and Mary style, the American ''kast'' featured removable feet, simplified the cornice, and eliminated the intricate [[inlay]]s favored by the Dutch.{{sfn|Butler|Johnson|Skibinski|1985|page=27}}

The "Boston chair" became one of the best-known examples of a William and Mary style chair made in America. This spoon-back chair{{Efn|The spoon-back chair features a back which curves slightly inward and then outward as it rises. The serpentine form looks like the curvature of a spoon handle, hence the name.{{sfn|Davidson|Stillinger|1985|page=110}}}} with leather-covered seat and splat featured turned front legs and a turned [[Stretcher (furniture)|stretcher]] between them. The side and rear stretcher as well as the rear legs, however, were undecorated straight lines. The corners of the frame around the splat were usually rounded down (although not turned), and the crest was a simplified geometric or curving design. They were usually painted black or red. Made primarily in [[Boston]], [[Massachusetts]], these chairs were manufactured in large numbers and very popular in America. They were also widely exported to Britain.{{sfn|Davidson|Stillinger|1985|page=110}} Benches and [[Couch|settees]] manufactured in America were less influenced by the William and Mary style. Panels, developed in the 1600s, were used for the seat, back, and (where used) arms, with trim and legs reflecting the new style. Leather seats were, however, sometimes added.{{sfn|Butler|Johnson|Skibinski|1985|page=26}}

Another innovation was the [[Tallboy (furniture)|highboy]].{{sfn|Gura|2016|page=16}} Essentially two chests of drawers, the lower slightly larger than the upper, American highboys often featured [[Solomonic column|Solomonic]] or [[trumpet]]-shaped legs. It was somewhat common for the faces of the drawers to have a walnut burl veneer.{{sfn|Butler|Johnson|Skibinski|1985|page=27}}

The William and Mary style lasted past the mid-1700s in rural America, often incorporating both Mannerist and Queen Anne styles. Slats began to be used in backs, and [[yoke]]-shaped crests became common.{{sfn|Davidson|Stillinger|1985|page=110}}

==Modern popularity==
The William and Mary style has long been overshadowed in both the [[United Kingdom]] and [[United States]] by the far more popular styles which came after it. Few reproductions of the furniture may be found today. However, numerous examples of William and Mary style furniture can still widely be found in British rural homes.{{sfn|Dillinger|2016|page=71}}

